        </div>

        <p>The LYBUNT/SYBUNT dashboard sits right alongside, showing you exactly who hasn&rsquo;t renewed and how much revenue is at risk. Together, these two dashboards transform retention from an annual statistic into a daily operating metric.</p>

        <p>You can also ask Fund-Raise&rsquo;s AI assistant retention questions directly: <em>&ldquo;What&rsquo;s our retention rate for donors who gave $5,000 or more?&rdquo;</em> or <em>&ldquo;How many first-time donors from FY2024 gave again in FY2025?&rdquo;</em> Instant answers, no pivot tables required.</p>

        <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

        <p>Donor retention rate isn&rsquo;t a vanity metric. It&rsquo;s the foundation&rsquo;s vital sign. A high retention rate means your donors trust you, feel valued, and believe their gifts make a difference. A low retention rate means you&rsquo;re leaking supporters faster than you can replace them &mdash; and no amount of acquisition spending can fix a broken bucket.</p>

        <p>Start by calculating your retention rate. Then calculate it for first-time donors specifically. If the number is below 25%, you have an urgent problem. If it&rsquo;s above 50%, you&rsquo;re outperforming most of the sector. Either way, now you know &mdash; and knowing is the prerequisite to improving.</p>

